Revolution, red gained new respect as the color of progressive movements and radical left-wing politics.In this beautifully illustrated book, Michel Pastoureau, the acclaimed author of Blue, Black, and Green, now masterfully navigates centuries of symbolism and complex meanings to present the fascinating and sometimes controversial history of the color red. Pastoureau illuminates red's evolution through a diverse selection of captivating images, including the cave paintings of Lascaux, the works of Renaissance masters, and the modern paintings and stained glass of Mark Rothko and Josef Albers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aColorxPsychological aspectsxHistory. 0aColorxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aRed in art. 0aRed. 0aSymbolism of colorsxHistory. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aAnthony van Dyck.  aAthanasius Kircher.  aBestiary.  aBlason.  aBrought to Light.  aCassone.  aChaperon (headgear).  aCharles the Bald.  aChurch Fathers.  aCinnabar.  aClassical Latin.  aClothing.  aCoat of arms.  aCochineal.  aCosmetics.  aCouleur.  aCouncil of Constance.  aDionysus.  aDyeing.  aEarly modern period.  aEinhard.  aEmblem.  aEnjolras.  aEtymology.  aFlemish painting.  aGeorges de La Tour.  aGiovanni Arnolfini.  aGood and evil.  aGrisaille.  aHebrews.  aHematite.  aHeraldry.  aHieronymus Bosch.  aHussites.  aIconography.  aInvidia.  aJacques Fabien Gautier d'Agoty.  aKees van Dongen.  aLacquer.  aLittle Red Riding Hood.  aLucas Cranach the Elder.  aMaurice Quentin de La Tour.  aMiddle French.  aMinium (pigment).  aMithraism.  aMuseo del Prado.  aNatural History (Pliny).  aOn the Eve.  aOrcein.  aOtto Dix.  aPaul Klee.  aPersecution.  aPhrygian cap.  aPigment.  aPolitique.  aPope Leo III.  aProstitution.